Mpho Raborife and Jeanette Chabalala, News24Students hold placards as they march toward the Union Buildings (Lerato Sejake, News24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Pretoria &ndash; A group of Fees Must Fall protesters has started marching to the Union Buildings in Pretoria calling for free tertiary education.The group had gathered at Church Square on Thursday morning, waiting for more students to join them.&nbsp;Less than 500 people were marching along Madiba Street. &nbsp;The group sang struggle songs and danced as they marched to the Union Buildings. Police were keeping a close watch on the protest. &nbsp;They held placards, some of which read "Blade must fall" and "Free education for all". Pupils wearing their school uniforms had also joined the march.&nbsp;READ: Fees Must Fall march on Union Buildings will be illegal - metro policeEarlier, Tshwane Metro Police spokesperson Senior Superintendent Isaac Mahamba said the group had not been granted permission to march and that the march would be considered illegal.If students marched despite this, a case would be opened.He would not clarify whether officers would move against the protesters."Any operational decision might be taken. We cannot disclose at this stage what decision may be taken, but any operational decision might be taken at that point," Mahamba said.The march was expected to begin at 08:00, but was delayed as students from other campuses were yet to be bused into town.School children have now joined the #FeesMarch to the #UnionBuildings. @News24 pic.twitter.com/0kJAza7kSC&mdash; Iavan Pijoos (@Iavan13) October 20, 2016School children have now joined the #FeesMarch to the #UnionBuildings. @News24 pic.twitter.com/0kJAza7kSC24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.